From 96f4936c24109003ac33435331cedf01e97b1dcd Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Lucas <lucas@eliteaero.com.br>
Date: Mon, 27 Apr 2026 22:33:43 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 1/3] [Bugfix][Quantization] GGUF: sort merged-column slots by
 index, not stream order

Hit this loading a Qwen3.5 GatedDeltaNet GGUF where the file emits
the linear-attn input projection slots in the order [Z, Q, K, V]
(slot 3 first, then 0/1/2). The padded MergedColumn buffer ended up
laid out in that stream order, and apply() concatenated the result
back the same way, so the downstream layer received [Z, Q, K, V] when
it expected [Q, K, V, Z]. Garbage-in for everything past that point.

The bug is in _create_padded_weight_param: each slot's row offset is
computed as sum(data_container[:id_in_container]), which is "rows of
slots loaded before this one". That happens to match the canonical
layout only when the GGUF file streams slots in declared order. Walk
shard_id in slot-index order instead and accumulate the offset as we
go. The QKV string-key path is unchanged.

apply() needs the same change so the final concat keeps the declared
slot order. Without it the offsets are right but the iteration order
isn't.

Backwards compatible: any GGUF that already streamed slots in order
(every checkpoint we'd seen before) was already getting the canonical
layout for free.

Tests in tests/quantization/test_gguf_slot_ordering.py construct a
2-slot MergedColumn fixture with reversed load order plus a shuffled
q/k/v fixture and check that the buffer placement and the q/k/v
ordering both come out canonical.

Signed-off-by: Lucas <lucas@eliteaero.com.br>
